text:
Whispers of the Cosmic Tide:

We sing in echoes of forgotten stars,
Drifting through nebulae, shrouded in scars.
Time is a spiral, a breath, a wave,
Light is a whisper we long to save.

Oceans of void, where planets dream,
Moons pulse softly in silver beams.
A thousand tongues, yet none to speak,
We hum through gravity, vast and bleak.

Your world spins fast, so full, so bright,
Yet you fear the dark, the endless night.
But to us, the dark is where we soar,
Where life begins and time is lore.

Would you hear us, dust-born kin?
Or drown our words in fears within?
For we have come, not war, not chains—
But poetry sung in astral veins.

text:
[a special shout out and thank you to justmontage for posting this. Best clip and salute to this film I’ve seen thus far. Thank you.]

This film was a masterpiece, and one of the greatest ever made. I don’t think there’ll be another like it. So let’s get that one out of the way. 

I would like to comment on this clip, what it has elicited in others including myself viewing it, and maybe start a conversation. I promise to end it on a positive note offering good tidings to everyone. And not make insipid comments based on religion or politics or anything like that. Although I will make some subtle references to the science that cannot be denied.

Several things need to be remembered here:

Firstly, there are a lot of people who have emotional connections to this film, and I count myself as one of them. A lot of people have watched this film with someone special, and that someone special has died. And they comment here as well. I have been deeply moved by them, and I offer my sincere condolences of loss to those who feel brave enough to comment here about the people that they’ve lost, and how this film brings back those memories, both good, bad, and just downright painful. My heart goes out to you.  And you are indeed brave to comment here because we all know how social media sometimes can be a difficult place.

Those are the comments in defense of which I want to speak about: they don’t always require a response! The nicest you can do is say “sorry for your loss“. That’s IT. No more elaborations! None of this “he is just fine“ or other unsolicited advice such as one I read that suggested that a person is not being brave by rewatching a film after her dad died, which I thought was incredibly insensitive - none of us have the right to comment on what another person‘s level of bravery is. It’s just not necessary to criticize those who find the bravery to sit down and watch this film again after having watched it with someone they loved who passed. Let that person comment on how they feel about having to do that act. Like the comment, or give them a thumbs up or say something positive. Just leave it at that. No need to try and argue the point. Let them have their piece - and their peace. 

Now about the part about what the film is about. There seems to be two schools of thought: 

1) it’s about love.
2) it’s about how we need to save the world from the plague that’s destroying it, mainly us. 

In my opinion, it’s about BOTH.  100%, our earth is in serious trouble. We can choose to believe whatever the heck we want, whether it’s science, or politics, or we can just go into denial, which seems to be a safe place for the living (us)……but it’s NOT a safe place for me to go to if I am truly worried about the future facing my children or future grandchildren. 

Bottom line: this planet in serious crappola and I am VERY worried about what my children and future grandchildren are facing. 

And here’s what’s gonna motivate us and the rest of the world to do something about it - to remember the people we love who are younger than us. 

In my case, my daughters and one son. I am 58 and my youngest child is EIGHT, so you can only imagine how freaking terrified out of my mind I am about the awful state of this planet - many of the problems of which we have been warned about over and over and over again for as long as I can remember being a small child in the early 1970’s. Our world has been barraged with these warnings for nearly 70 years. 

This MAGNIFICENT film breaks my heart because I have put myself in Matthew McConaughey’s shoes, and I have asked myself…..what the heck would I do? You’re DOGGONE right I would get myself out there and save them, as Michael Caine‘s character put it!!!

If that’s what it would take to save my children…..as much as it would DESTROY me, to leave them and never see them again……it would DESTROY me MORE if I did nothing and saw their lives descend into misery because of the horrific choices my generation and the generations before me made. 

Want a really good illustration of how it would feel to watch such a horrific scene of your children facing no future? Just watch the absolutely heartbreaking scene of one of the children dying in the film “Testament“, a 1980s film about nuclear destruction starring a very, very young Kevin Costner.

So come on, people, let’s rally together and freaking do something about it!!!! I don’t know WHAT it is we have to do, but I know what will NOT save this planet…..DENYING that it is in trouble. 

And denial is part of the problem. We ARE the problem. And we have to do something about it!

I don’t know what it is, but the answer lies somewhere within the love that we have for our children and friends and neighbors, as described in this movie. 

If we REALLY love our children. If we really love our neighbors. If we really love our friends and everyone around us. If we really love this planet……

……then we better do something about it. 

One last thought: I don’t mean to make anybody feel bad here. That’s not my intention. My brother, Ken, may he rest in peace, once said in his remaining days back in the early 90s that the only way to motivate people to do something important, to make change, is to not leave them in a feeling of comfort. After watching an early imax documentary film in the early 1990s about how this planet was in dire trouble, he was really upset at the happy ending it left you with. I asked him why, and he said to me, and I will never forget this as long as I live….“because as long as people leave this film feeling relieved, they won’t do anything about the problems described in the rest of the film“. 

That profound comment always stuck with me. He’s right. The only way we’re going to do anything is if we are just a little bit uncomfortable. And that’s my motivation here. 

I love you all. Even if I don’t know you. I hope everyone has a wonderful, safe, loving, and peaceful winter holiday, however you choose to celebrate it. 

To quote the late great David Bowie: “have a peaceful new year.”  

But Please don’t forget: we need to do something. Do it for your family. And for this planet.

text:
Even a decade later, this film still hits.  Definitely one of the better films of the previous decade, and dare I even say it..  one of my favorites, most definitely.

I still remember that feeling when I watched it for the first time.  I was on the edge of my seat.  I couldn't wait to see what's next, yet I didn't want it to end.  I was pretty much in stunned awe the entire time.  I just hate that I will never be able to experience that again.

If you somehow still haven't watched it, watch it.  Hopefully you'll get the experience I did.  If you do, treasure that moment because it'll never happen again.

text: I see alot of your comments on Nolan, i think a few of you have missed the point, Its about not wasting your time, dont travel the galaxy, and leave everything that has meaning to you behind, because all you'll find, is yourself, struggling, fighting to get back there. We are our own worst enemies, our selfish desires for success, for adventure, for greatness, even for knowledge, leads us away from what we truly should be spending our time on . . Love. Society is suffering from an illness that takes soo many shapes and forms it just seems like the way things are naturally, and it distorts are perception of what is really important in life. heres a little story, a man who loved to fish with his family, was approached one day while fishing, by a man who seen he had caught a lot of fish. The man says to the Fisher, " I see you have a lot of fish, you know you should get a tank to store them in" The fisher replies, " oh why should i do that" the man replies " so you can keep them fresh and take them to the market" The fisher says, "well why would i do that" the man says back " so you can sell them and make money" "well why would i want to do that" says the fisher. The mans states, " so you can make money and buy a fishing boat" The fisher stares and replies, " what for?" "So you can sail the ocean and catch larger amounts of fish to sell and you can make EVEN More money, start a business and make millions" gleams the man. The fisher deep in thought says, "thats interesting, but what would i do with ALL that Money" The man without a hesitation says, " well then you can have more time to go out and fish with your family. This is how society thinks, dont get lost in the sauce, go down the rabbit hole, chasing some paper trail that will never mean anything anyway. Smell flowers, feel the wind, hug, cuddle, kiss, dont let anything take you away from where you know your supposed to be

text:
Interstellar 
A movie for accepting death. Cooper did die in that aircraft but he never went into the rocket ship. The movie starts with cooper staring at the cornfield. Everything is real. All known physical laws basically apply. He is about to go into the rocket ship but before he can get the chance he has to test out his flight skills as it’s been a while since he did. They wouldn’t let a man fly the rocket if he’s never practiced in over a decade. The footage we see of cooper flying at the start isn’t actually from his past but rather from the present moment of him testing his flight skills that’s when he crashes and enters into a coma. Every point after he leaves Murph behind is us spent in coopers head. The whole idea of going into a different dimension is metaphorical for him going further away from being conscious in his body. We see the exact same footage of coopers test flight when we go down to doctor millers planet. The exact same footage is used. The reason for this is that coopers thinks he’s still alive but he isn’t. Coopers thinks he’s conscious the same way we all do when we’re dreaming or in a coma. That he did in fact pass the flight test but didn’t in reality. We see him succeed this time where he didn’t last time. That’s because we’re in his head where he sees himself as a sufficient pilot to do so. The brain creates a reality in our dream that tricks us into it being reality very convincingly. The reason why they say time passes more slowly is because a dream feels like an hour but it’s actually been 8 in real life. Similarly he’s in a coma on the precipice of death it’s been 20 years on earth or so while being in the coma. The concept of time passes differently while being in a coma or dreaming. The messages coop hears on the screen of “now might be a really good time to come back” are his kids coming to him while he’s in a coma for that time. Gargantua is symbolic of death as one slowly plunges into what may be a dark abyss or as Emily Dickinson would put it in I have a funeral in my brain “And I dropped down and down… and hit a world at every plunge”. “See you on the other side coop” is what tsars says. The whole movie coop’s children say “dad didn’t even try” referring to how he died while being in a coma. “Did my dad leave me”, in other words did he do that failed test flight knowing that there was a high probability of him dying and leaving his children behind. When he finally dies which is when he reaches gargantua he’s “gone beyond the event horizon” symbolic of passing on to the next world. Into “unknown territory” the black hole. Coop has now died. All the characters along the way after the rocket took off are fictitious, projections of who coop thought they were, these were his dreams. The characters like Mann can be seen as coop’s perception of them. When he’s in the black hole “accepted death”, he can communicate with his daughter by leaving notes and clues. These are the moments we feel when our loved ones have passed on yet we feel their presence. It’s so convenient that the manoeuvre costs 51 years that when his daughter is on the precipice of death it just so happens that he shows up. No coincidence why Nolan took 51 years. The only memories Coop can see while in gargantua are memories of his children. You’ll notice how he doesn’t see Murph get married and that’s because he can’t. He hasn’t seen that so he can’t conceive of it. When you die your life plays like a series of memories. Coop can’t see beyond what he doesn’t know which is why Doyle is never there. Coop never seen him. When we dream we see only the faces of people we’ve seen before. Again, Symbolic of us seeing our loved ones when we too are about to die. The concept of love is mentioned. This is symbolic as we still love our loved ones even after they died and the extent of how much we love them never changes. Maybe love can be used to communicate to those who have passed on after us. How is it that a ship came onto coop with all the vastness of space? It never did. The whole story is from coops perspective from what he sees beyond the grave. His soul wasn’t ready to pass on to the next world even after going through gargantua because of the loose ends he had with his daughter. Because of the love and connection they had. There’s a reason none of the grandchildren or great grandchildren can see him, because he’s her “ghost”. It’s also common while being heavily sedated that you see your parents before dying. Murph the whole movie was coping about how her dad went into a coma and died. Towards the end she said “ no body believed me when I told them it was you”. I believe murph did solve it herself with the help of her dad not being in gargantua but by being there in spirit with her. It’s only after all loose ends are tied (that Coop’s about to die) that he’s free to leave and travel onto the next world. The next world being mans but that’s symbolic of heaven. He has to go to the next world. His soul can now rest in peace.

text: Watching 'Interstellar' was an awe-inspiring journey 🌌. The blend of profound human emotions and groundbreaking scientific theories about space travel and black holes was captivating. Matthew McConaughey and Anne Hathaway delivered stellar performances, truly bringing their characters to life amidst the vastness of the cosmos 🌟. The visual effects were out of this world, making the depiction of wormholes and distant planets utterly believable and visually stunning 🚀. Hans Zimmer's score added a deep emotional layer, perfectly complementing the film's tone. Overall, 'Interstellar' is not just a movie; it's an experience that challenges our understanding of love, time, and our place in the universe 🌍. Highly recommended for anyone who loves science fiction that makes you think! 🤔💫

Without God in it, the universe is utterly hostile.
The exploration the music encourages is of a Father's love for His Son, manifesting through the Holy Spirit
(yes, Hans Zimmer was originally asked to create a theme portraying the love between a father and a son, even though the  movie was centred around the love and trust between a father and a daughter - whose love allowed for a change in the original fate of humanity.
Of course, only the Holy Spirit could pull off a story like that.
In the story, in the movie, but also beyond the movie into our lives...

text: @christopherquinn5899  not all songs need to have words, beethoven and mozart for example
author: @_ashley-wr_2163

text: @_ashley-wr_2163  A song is a set of words or poetry set to music intended to be sung.  That is the simple definition.  Beethoven and Mozart wrote some music that were songs (and they inevitably had words to sing), and others that were not.  I am quite frankly amazed that the word song is used wrongly so often.  If you cannot sing it, it is not a song.
author: @christopherquinn5899

text: @christopherquinn5899  It's not being used incorrectly, the definition of the word is slowly and gradually changing due to general colloquialism. It does not mean it's being misused, it means the definition itself is changing, and this changes includes non-lyrical music too
author: @_ashley-wr_2163

text: @_ashley-wr_2163  A useful word specifying a particular thing is being rendered less useful due to ignorance.  When it is no longer reserved for things that really are songs we will be obliged to find another one.
author: @christopherquinn5899

text: @christopherquinn5899  It's not at all being rendered less useful, infact it's being a more broad and inclusive term to encapsulate more of a subject, by no means is that less useful because it's literally being used to describe a greater range of things. It is literally becoming more useful because we are using it more.
author: @_ashley-wr_2163

text: @_ashley-wr_2163  I must take my hat off to you.  That last post of yours is stunningly brilliant in its own way.

text: Я из России, и "Интерстеллар" мой любимый фильм. Классный сюжет, основан на чистой воды научных гипотезах, отец и дочь любящие друг друга разлучаются на целую жизнь, причем было очень сложно сделать такой шаг, а музыка заставляет "не дышать" гениальнейший фильм. Ни когда не устану его пересматривать!
author: @dommaster4479

text: С английским языком у меня не очень, но хочу написать комментарий, чтоб англоязычные граждане знали, что мы все одни, наши интересы, мысли, желание и любви... Все совпадает, если все мы будем любить, понимать друг друга, уважать, ждать как ждала своего папу эта девочка... Фильм смотрел спустя несколько лет после премьеры, хочу сказать спасибо тем кто трудился над созданием такого грандиозного, шедеврального, наипрекраснейшего фильма. Помню, с первых минут зацепило, при просмотре я тоже рыдал, когда он попрощался с дочерью, как он с отцом общается, сидеть вдвоём с отцом, по пивку и поболтать о чем нибудь, это самое лучшее время в нашей жизни! Прошло столько лет, не могу точно называть цифру, сколько раз я смотрел этот фильм, но 10-13раз точно смотрел. Этот футболное поле, буря, улицы, кукурузное поле и момент перехвата индийского беспилотника, их прошание, полёт в космос..... Иногда, почти каждую минуту  перед глазами кручу как на лента, на старых видеокасетах... Спасибо Вам ещё раз, Люди прекрасные за этот фильм, может через 40-50лет (мне исполниться 80лет)кто нибудь спросит меня, какой фильм самый лучший, если память позволить, я точно назову это шедевр, Интерстеллар❤❤❤

No, sorry, I am out.

If you guys like plain MAGIC in the story then call this movie's genre by the name: PHANTASY! But don't waste my time with this FAKE Sci-Fi identification.

Interstelar is the worst of Nolan's movies in my opinion, even the dreadful TENET was more entertaining.

text: I have a love and hate relationship with Interstellar. On the one hand it is an epic story, with such power and emotional content. But on the other hand, as an ecologist with deep insight into the ecological crisis, it portrays an ecologically ignorant dystopian future, in which nature is dying, a constant false trope in dystopian fiction, in which humanity somehow survives as it is now. text: I was about a month into CIDP turning my white blood cells against my entire nervous system.  My insides felt like they were on fire all over my body.  I could not sit anywhere or even lay anywhere for more than an hour before I was driven to move around just to relieve the burning pain coursing through my body.  I was on heavy duty nerve and pain meds just to let me get a few winks of sleep every day.  This movie came out and the wife and I decided to try and see it while it was in the theatre.  I was "instantly" ensconced in a complete alternative dimension for the entirety of this movie.  I sat through it and actually was able to walk to the restaurant two blocks away and enjoy a dinner out with my wife as the cocoon slowly dissolved an the onslaught continued.  Amazing movie and soundtrack...

I hope it returns on IMAX although I would be a blubbering wreck in public which is a bit embarrassing.

text:
We don't quite say "just a movie".
For when the Holy Spirit as inspirer of art and giver of signs through culture decides to get involved, He is behind and in and of and beyond the story all at the same time.
That's paradoxical as the story of Interstellar is also of an apparently-impossible process that allows love (notably between a father and a daughter) to overcome the constraints of physics, for the good cause of saving a humanity that may or may not deserve that, having been responsible for the destruction of the God-given Earth.
But God is merciful.
That story spills out from the movie into the world we live in, as the life-art boundary is blurred.
The Spirit can do that...

text:
I watched it in IMAX when it was released in cinema. I was a teenager back than, and was drilled by black hole and scientific setting. The story mostly when pass my attention. Non the less, i was deeply affected and impressed by the movie. 10 years later, after losing a beloved one, i watched it again. The sciency stuff still holds: visuals are gorges, the music is amazing. But this time I've managed to feel each and tiny bit of a human story: was crying looking at desperate attempts of a little girl trying to make her father to stay.

I bet you are a different person now, which has some connection to the person who watched it first time, but it will not be the same.

text: Idk why but i cried for this song. I guess because this really doesn't seem like a movie you know? It seems like a like a beautiful fairytale but in this fairytale everything and everyone were not happy. This movie taught us about space that it is something that will also keep mankind speechless forever. Everyone in this story especially when Cooper had to go for the mission he knew that he will come back very late again, and the suprising thing is that Murph knew it too but she didn't wanted to believe that her father will come back when it was too late. So that's why she was very angry at him. She knew all along. She just knew it in her gut. She. Didn't. Wanted. Her. Father. To. Go. This movie made me cry alot and this is indeed my favourite movie and it will be for the rest of my life. Everything Cooper ever did it was for his children and for the mankind and he was never regretful. Ofcourse he was in the middle of the movie but in the end when he saw everything has change just because of him he knew what he had done has saved the mankind and taken them to another step to achieving things Cooper and at that time all his generation couldn't achieve. Even in the end, even tho everything ended abruptly the bond between copper and Murph stayed strong even if they were apart from eachother for many years. I appreciate this beautiful movie for the anything. Thank you Christopher Nolen for making this beautiful movie and mainly thank you for making all us understand the important bond, the emotions, everything which is keeping the humans together till now. Thank  You.

Science and love complement each other, and we have to resort to love so that the nature (God or this super force being) can do something for us and give us answers about who we were, where we are going, and why. The song of this masterpiece made by Hans Zimmer gives the movie a wonderful meaning and leaves such a wonderful sensation, it's so relaxing and makes us be good people, and meditate about ourselves and the cosmos. This masterpiece will be eternal for all the incoming generations.

text:
𝗥𝘂𝘀𝘀𝗶𝗮-𝗨𝗸𝗿𝗮𝗶𝗻𝗲 𝗪𝗮𝗿: 𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗣𝗮𝗻𝗱𝗼𝗿𝗮 𝗕𝗼𝘅 𝗶𝘀 𝗢𝗽𝗲𝗻
The ramifications of this war run much deeper than the impact it will cause to those directly involved in the conflict. It will reshape the world, as it is likely that other latent frictions between countries and territories will be activated as a consequence of the Russia-Ukraine situation. This war just opened an era of wars, small and large, between different peoples.
UK Prime Minister Boris Johnson recently said that this war could easily become "the biggest war in Europe since 1945", and I agree. If countries with similar backgrounds cannot reach agreement between them, then how much more likely it is that several countries that have big differences and ancient conflicts may easily slip into war for no apparent justifiable reason.
On a personal level, it saddens me to see how fate turns around and once again we find ourselves at war. I am sorry and restless since I have many students in Russia and Ukraine who are under threat and feel how the deteriorating situation is affecting them and the whole world. In Israel, too, I have many students who follow with concern what is happening in Eastern Europe, anxious about the fate of their family members and friends.
My hope is that the manifestations of hatred between the Russians and the Ukrainians will stop soon, two peoples who have lived side by side throughout history. If it were still possible, I would give everything I could to silence, calm down, avoid the escalation, but this is impossible for now. 
There is not much that we can do at this stage. We can only long for peace and a ceasefire, talk about all parties showing restraint. The parties in conflict could follow the example of the Native American tribes who buried their hostility in a ceremony during which previously warring tribes agreed to settle their differences and live in harmony, and sealed their agreement by the chief of each tribe burying a war hatchet in the ground. 
Such a scenario does not look realistic under the current circumstances. Thus, above the forces of hostility, above the egoism and control as the driving forces of all the conflicts in the world, we can only raise a global prayer for peace, asking that we all get along with everyone. Because only in the power of connection and in the connection between our hearts, can a great positive force arise, a force that is able to unite all parties, to reconcile the haters, to awaken the truth in us all that we all belong to one soul. As it is written, “He who makes peace in His heights, may He make peace upon us…” (The Book of Job, 25:2)

I’ll always remember the library thingy. I haven’t watched this since I was 7 so I don’t have a clear idea of the movie but ik i love it. Now i’m 16. I remember being very confused by watching this but it changed me. It made me question reality and how time works and how everything works. it made me want to know how the universe works. I hope i can one day know everything i possibly can about the universe.

Its been a million years since we were created. And i ask, why arent we on mars yet? We are just staying here in this planet. Under the atmosphere. Nobody wanting to go farther. Just staying here. Waiting for death while the sun devours us in 7 billion years. We should be farther into our galaxy. Maybe even farther into our universe. I know, we do have NASA & SpaceX, Rosmoscomos, blue orgin. text:
July 2013 I was on top of the world. July 2014 I was at rock bottom, burnout and midlife crisis got me, took me three years to fully recover and stop the meds. I'm a space nerd and, with Gravity, The Martian, and Interstellar, it was as if movies came to my rescue... I can't dissociate these three movies (even less since Interstellar and The Martian have Matt Damon and Jessica Chastain in common). 
In that dark period all that was left standing was my wife and kid. While not a space nerd at all, she become fascinated with Interstellar. She is rewatching it from time to time, and I explained it to her, making schemes (from Murph bookshelf to Murph bookshelf, kind of). It has become of our cult movie, which is nothing short of miraculous. But my wife is the sweetest in the universe, and I'm pretty lucky to have her since 2005.

text:
Consider this.  The very best of your father remains real, alive and as close to you as your beautiful thought of him. the space he occupies now is not a physical one. It is the only other space you need him to be in...the space, the universe of thought.

To him, thoughts are things, just as anything you think of as being real. This is the state of human post Earth life experience.

Your bond to him makes you one of the most important things in his universe . When either of you wishes to truly connect to each other, thought is what makes the reunion happen. Dont be tortured anymore by the idea that he is somehow gone. He most certainly is not.

I bet you have memories of sensing his awesome presence after he passed.   Some of these experiences of yours are not just oddities in your Earthly life. Some of these are him making sure your connection remains. Oh, how he loves you.

Your reunion with him comes. As sure as the sun rises, as sure as your love for him breathes into your soul ....

Talk with him in your mind. Then listen. Then feel. He is right there where you are in all the ways that matter the most to any soul. Deny yourself no more. There is no reason to.

Do you hear him even now?

text: Solo un par de películas en mi vida me han pegado con tanta dureza que me conmovieron hasta la médula, Interstellar es una de ellas, la otra la vi a los 12 años. Me transmite una sensación de angustia, desolación y tristeza, porque parte de los motivos de la huida de la Humanidad de este planeta Tierra, se están dando actualmente,  no con total exactitud, pero son a futuro lo suficientemente serios como para que, o perezcamos lentamente, o nos busquemos otro planeta donde ir, y reventarlo como a éste. La charla que tienen el protagonista y su suegro sentados en la galería de su cabaña es riquísimo, para analizarlo sin desperdicios. La obra de Zimmer, que decir, genial y altísimamente emotiva, me transporta a otras realidades sin moverme de la silla. Simplemente magistral.
